<entry done=TRUE>shirt
<lex>
<sen uid=506479  ord=1 tag=garment>
<gr>nc; often with mod</gr>
<def>a garment worn on the upper part of the body, especially by men, with a collar and sleeves and usually buttons down the front</def>
<ex>He was wearing slacks and an open-necked shirt.</ex>
<ex>He unbuttoned his shirt.</ex>
<ex>He put on a clean white shirt and a suit.</ex>
<ex>&ellip. dressed in shirt and jeans.</ex>
<kind>HAIR SHIRT, polo shirt, T-SHIRT</kind>
<sen uid=521306  ord=1a tag=garmod>
<gr>n-mod</gr>
<def>modifying another noun</def>
<ex>He loosened his shirt collar.</ex>
<ex>Another offered me toffees and put a tiny plastic cross in my shirt pocket.</ex></sen>
<sen uid=506540  ord=1.1 tag=sport>
<gr>nc; usu after mod</gr>
<def>a shirt (of distinctive colour and pattern) worn by a member of a sports team; often in metonymic use referring to membership of a particular team</def>
<ex>Fly-half John Liley pulls on the No 10 shirt for England in the opening match.</ex>
<ex>Goalminder Jeff Smith increased his chances of a Great Britain shirt later this month with a penalty shot save.</ex>
<ex>The first Roman Catholic to don the blue shirt of the club's first team.</ex>
<kind>football shirt, rugby shirt, sports shirt</kind>
<note>or do the kinds belong with sense 1</note></sen></sen></lex></entry>

